-- Brazil Stocks: Eletropaulo, Gol, Oi, Petrobras and Vale
-- B y   E d u a r d o   T h o m s o n
-- 2012-05-04T20:49:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-04/brazil-stocks-eletropaulo-gol-linhas-aereas-jbs-oi.html
The following companies had  unusual 
price changes in Brazilian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the close in  Sao Paulo .
Preferred shares are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The  Bovespa (IBOV)  Index fell 2.1 percent to 60,820.93.  Eletropaulo Metropolitana SA (ELPL4 BS) dropped 4.2 percent
to 28.47 reais for the steepest fall in two weeks. The provider
of electricity to Sao Paulo reported a 61 percent decrease in
first-quarter profit to 110 million reais ($57.1 million).  Gol Linhas Aereas Inteligentes SA (GOLL4)  (GOLL4 BS) rose 5.2
percent to 10.54 reais, the most in more than two weeks.
 Brazil ’s second-largest airline by market share isn’t planning
any more flight cancellations and will spin off its frequent-
flier program by the first half of next year, Chief Executive
Officer Constantino de Oliveira said today on a conference call.
The company posted a surprise first-quarter loss as fuel costs
increased and the real slid.  Oi SA (OIBR4)  (OIBR4 BS) retreated 2 percent to 9.83 reais. The
Brazilian telecommunications company was rated sell in new
coverage at Citigroup Inc.  Petroleo Brasileiro SA (PETR4)  (PETR4 BS) dropped 4.3 percent to
20.48 reais, the steepest fall in almost three months. Brazil’s
state-controlled oil producer sank to the lowest in more than
six months after a production halt by its partner Chevron Corp.
contributed the lowest domestic output since August.  Vale SA (VALE3)  (VALE3 BS), the world’s largest iron-ore producer,
retreated 2.9 percent to 41.53 reais. Brazil’s Superior Court of
Justice canceled a March 14 ruling that freed Vale from making
collateral payments as part of a dispute over 30.7 billion reais
worth of taxes claimed by the government, the company said in a
statement late yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
